(Dataset Exploration of the FordGo Bike trips in February 2019)¶

by (Louaye Lamaa)¶

This dataset contains data about the individual trips of the FordGo bike in the San Fransisco area. This notebook explores the main features of the trip such as start and end station, duration, and time as well as the characteristics of the riders such as age, gender and if a user is a customer or subscriber.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains data about 183412 trips with 14 variables (duration of the trip, start and end time /start and end station id, name and coordinates/gender, year of birth and type of the users/ service bike share for all). The most variables - after cleaning- are categorical. The numeric variables are duration, age, and coordinates.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am intrested to see how the duration and time of the trips vary based on the characterstics of the users in term of age, gender, customer or subscriber.

  • What time the bikes are most used (day of week, day of the month, hour of the day)?
  • The duration of the trips ?
  • What are the characteristics of the users in term of age, gender and type and how these feature are related to the duration and time of the trips ?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the gender, age and user type will have an impact on the duration of the trips. Also, I expect user type will have an effect on the time the trips are taken. In addition, the time of the trip could have an effect on its duration. I expect that the start and end station might have an slight effect on the duration.

Tidiness:¶

  • start and end time have three variables : date of month, day of week , hour of the day.
  • create a new column for age from the birth date column.

Quality:¶

1) duration is better to be in minutes for clearer analysis 2) Errorneous datatypes:

  • duration (in minutes) to datetime
  • start_station_id and end_station_id and bike_id to string
  • user_type, member_gender, day of week and hour of day to category

On the log scalled plot, we can see a unimodal normal distibution with a peak at around 10 minutes. Most durations fall between 5 and 15 minutes. There is very high values that could be outliers, should be handled to give us a better analysis since the 3rd percentile is 13 while we have some values bigger than 500. I will use clipping method to handle these values. There is different features that could affect the duration such as user type or age. I will analyze the relationship between duration and other factors in the next part.

In [26]:
#disribution have outliers from the high ==> clipping 
# upper limit - .99 quantile ==> clipped by 99 percent quantile (all points falls outside this range will reduced the upper value of the range)
upper_limit = df_clean['duration_mins'].quantile(0.99) + 30
# lower limit - .05 quantile
lower_limit = df_clean['duration_mins'].quantile(0.0)
df_clean['duration_quantile'] = df_clean['duration_mins'].clip(lower_limit, upper_limit, axis = 0)

In [29]:
# easier when working with multivariate analysis
def log_trans(x,inverse=False):
    """ Transform a column to log scale """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10,x)
df_clean['log_duration_quantile'] = df_clean['duration_quantile'].apply(log_trans)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trips are more common in the weekdays than in the weekends. The hour of day distrbution shows two peaks at the start and end of the work day, at 8-9 am and 5-6 pm. The majority of the riders are male, and the most of the users are subscribers and don't use the bike all share service. The age of the most riders is between 25 and 40 with some older users above 75 years old. The duration of trips took on a large range of high values, so I applied a log transfomation to look at the data. The log distrbution shows that the most of the trips lasts between 5 and 15 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The age of the users has some unsual distribution with very old bikers, so I decided to remove the obervations with age higher than 75. To make the data easier to analyze, I created columns for the hours of the day, and type of the day (weekend and weekday) from the start time column. Also, I calculated the age of the riders from the year of birth as it is easier to understand, and I transformed the seconds into minutes as it is clearer to interpret.

def hist2grid(x,y,**kwargs):
    '''Draw a heatmap in the seaborn FacetGrid'''
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    x_bin = np.arange(x.min(),x.max()+4,4)
    y_bin = np.arange(y.min(),y.max()+0.2,0.2)
    plt.hist2d(x,y,bins=[x_bin,y_bin],cmap=palette,cmin=0.5)
    plt.yticks(log_trans(np.array([1,3,10,30,100])),

#prepare data to plot in heatmap
def pivotToHeatMap(data,*args):
    d = data.groupby([args[0],args[1]]).size()
    d= d.reset_index(name=args[2])
    d = d.pivot(index=args[0], columns=args[1], values=args[2])
    return d

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The analysis of the duration of the trips and age with the gender and type of the users prove that the duration depends on the age. Since the female users are younger than the male users, the duration of the trips taken by the female users are longer.

The duration of the trips in the weekend is higher than the duration during the rest of the days. This trend is observed among customers and subscribers (the trend is clearer among customers). This shows that the day of the week affects the duration of the trips, and since the trips duration of the customers is higher than the trips duration of the subscribers in the weekend, the purpose of the customers is not just usage for work as the subscribers. The analysis of the duration of the trips by the hour of the day among customers and subscribers shows the customers ride more during the middle of the day while subscribers tend to use the bikes more at 8-9 am and 5-6 pm, which explains why the trips of the customers took more time as they use the bike for all purpose (sports or during leisure time) including work.The distribution of the trips between customers and subscribers prove that the duration here is affected by the purpose of each user type (and so the day of usage). This distribution shows that the customers bike much more during the weekend than the subscribers while the subscribers use these bikes during the weekday, specifically in the morning around 8 am and after noon around 5 pm.
